[1] Huanglongbing, citrus - Viet Nam: control by guava interplanting
[2] Huanglongbing, citrus - USA (Florida): trial of guava interplanting
******
[1] Huanglongbing, citrus - Viet Nam: control by guava interplanting
Date: Wed 8 Aug 2007
Source: Fresh Plaza, VietNamNet Bridge report [edited]
<http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=5415>

For over 10 years now, the farmers growing oranges in Tuong Loc
Commune (Tam Binh District, Vinh Long Province) have faced the
continuous worry of the spread of citrus disease by the Asian citrus
psyllid pest, which causes severe drops in crop productivity. A woman
in the area, however, has discovered a measure to avoid such ill fortune.
After 3 years of growth, her dream orchard had not yet produced its
1st crop as the citrus disease set in. Others in Tam Binh were also
infected by the disease, and nobody knew how to cope with it, relying
on pesticides, which scarcely affected the Asian citrus psyllid pest.
In mid 2006, [the woman] learned that the orange orchard of [a man]
in Cai Be of Tien Giang province had escaped the effects of the
disease although all surrounding orchards were [infected]. She
immediately paid a visit to [the man's] orchard and found that
_Psidium guajava_ trees were growing between the orange ones. [The
woman] brought home a young _Psidium guajava_ to grow in her orange orchard.
Shortly afterwards, she witnessed the recovery of the leaves on her
orange trees growing near the _Psidium guajava_. To double-check her
results, she plucked all the leaves from the _Psidium guajava_ --
surely enough, the orange trees became re-infected. At present, many
farmers in Tam Binh grow _Psidium guajava_ between their orange trees
to protect them from the citrus disease. The orange trees have
returned to the health they had known 10 years ago.
Dr. Ngo Vinh Vien, director of the Plant Protection Institute, has
confirmed the ability of the _Psidium guajava_ to fight the
disease-spreading bug. "Japanese scientists have already known about
this unique phenomenon, and have appointed specialists to Tam Binh to
do research on it." Dr. Vien added, "To save orange growers from
going bankrupt due to the disease, this method should be recommended
to other districts and provinces. However, further studies to uncover
the interactions between the pest and the _Psidium guajava_ should be
conducted before doing so."
--
